<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Berlusconi tries to repair damage of Fininvest row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi last night sought to restore his credibility with a
public address aimed at solving the controversial issue of his conflicting
interest as Italian prime minister and owner of the Fininvest media empire.
As part of a parliamentary debate called by the opposition, Mr Berlusconi
offered to make even more watertight his separation from Fininvest, Italy's
second-largest private group which controls 80 per cent of commercial
television. He said he was prepared to 'accept any technical solution' that
was suggested by parliament.
This was a significant softening of the position he outlined only last
Friday. But in a defensive speech, occasionally interrupted by opposition
jeering, he appeared willing to trade parliament's agreement on this issue
in return for a solid mandate to continue governing.
Speaking for the opposition, Mr Massimo D'Alema, leader of the former
communist Party of the Democratic Left, insisted the conflict of interest
was so great that Mr Berlusconi had to approve a break-up of his Fininvest
television interests. He said Mr Berlusconi was incapable of addressing the
issue as a statesman because he was too involved in protecting his business
activities from investigating magistrates.
The toughest speech in the debate came from Mr Berlusconi's partner in
government, Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of the populist Northern League, who
attacked the prime minister for failing to settle the conflict of interest
before taking office.
Mr Bossi said the league would present proposals within the next few days.
In a first stage, Mr Berlusconi would have to be separated clearly from the
management of Fininvest. Second, Fininvest interests must be placed in a
closed fund. This suggests the league will favour sale of his assets, if not
creation of a special foundation.
Mr Bossi showed he intended to use the league's role in formulating
legislation as a weapon to continue humiliating Mr Berlusconi - although he
pledged not to bring down the government.
The debate marked the second time in five days that Mr Berlusconi has had to
confront problems created by his ownership of Fininvest. Last Friday, he
proposed the creation of a five-member commission to monitor any conflict of
interest that might arise, plus an administrator to represent his interests
as Fininvest's dormant proprietor.
This followed opposition concern over the way Mr Berlusconi had become
dragged into a conflict between the executive and the judiciary over
investigations by Milan anti-corruption magistrates into Fininvest.
Last Friday, Mr Berlusconi's younger brother, Paolo, handed himself in to
Milan magistrates. He later admitted to paying L330m (Pounds 135,000) in
bribes to members of the Guardia di Finanza, the financial police, over the
inspections of three Fininvest companies. His lawyer said the payments had
been made under duress.
</TEXT>
