<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Being typecast is not a problem for Jane Horrocks the waif-like actress
whose recent roles have ranged from Sally Bowles in the stage version of
Cabaret to the fluffy secretary in Absolutely Fabulous. Tonight (BBC 2 at
9.25pm) in Suffer the Little Children she tackles a more emotionally
demanding role (reviewed above by Clement Crisp).
Man the Hunter is the theme of Desmond Morris's second investigation of The
Human Animal (BBC 1 at 9.30). There is a kind of spurious intellectualism
over the attempt to explain that the competitiveness and violence men needed
when hunting for food is now chanelled into sport. Where does this leave the
development of woman? Is she unchanged and should she stay minding the
children and the hearth?
In Witness (Channel 4 at 9 pm) former nun Karen Armstrong lays the blame for
the ills of the world at the feet of the current Pope who she sees as a
reactionary absolute monarch. Not much Christian charity observable here. At
11pm on the same channel Darcus Howe plays Devil's Advocate, quizzing Imran
Khan about cricketers' dirty tricks.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
