<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Surveyors face tougher rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Surveyors will be subject to tougher rules on the way they conduct
valuations, under draft guidelines unveiled yesterday by the Royal
Institution of Chartered Surveyors.
They will be obliged for the first time to state valuation instructions
explicitly in writing and agree them with clients. If there are
uncertainties in the valuation because of market conditions or other special
circumstances, these must be flagged in the surveyor's report.
Mr Adrian Britton, director of the general practice division of the
institution, said: 'We are quite determined that we are not going to have
valuations undertaken without both parties being clear about what the
service is.'
He said insurance companies had advised the institution that 45 per cent of
professional indemnity claims against surveyors would not have arisen if the
instructions had been written down.
The new rules will be compulsory and will replace two existing sets of
rules, only one of which was mandatory. The present mandatory rules cover
how valuations should take place but only for a limited number of types of
valuation. The other set of rules has information on producing and
conducting valuations.
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
