<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Bank sticks to inflation forecast but sees short-term
decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England yesterday admitted that inflation had turned out to be
lower than expected in its last quarterly report and reduced its short-term
forecast of underlying inflation.
Nevertheless, its latest quarterly inflation report warned that, unless base
rates were increased at some point in the months ahead, underlying inflation
would be in the top half of the government's 1 per cent to 4 per cent target
range in two years.
That would conflict with the government's aim of reducing such inflation to
the lower half of the band by the end of this parliament or no later than
the second quarter of 1997.
The Bank expects underlying retail price inflation (the so-called RPIX,
which excludes mortgage interest payments) to fall to about 2.3 per cent
over the next three months from 2.4 per cent in June. Underlying inflation
will be lower than previously thought until the end of 1995 before peaking
above 3 per cent in the first quarter of 1996.
The Bank's own measure of core inflation, RPIY (which also excludes local
authority and indirect taxes) fell to a record low of 1.6 per cent in April.
The report lowers the forecast for RPIY, which is expected to remain below 3
per cent in the next two years.
Three factors have caused the Bank to alter its projections. The first, says
the report, is that 'inflation has been lower than expected over the past
three months. The squeeze on profit margins, which started in the fourth
quarter of 1993 in food retailing, has spread.'
Second, the Bank now says that the disinflationary pressure has proved
greater than anticipated. In particular, the squeeze on retail margins is
unlikely to be reversed in the near future.
The third factor cited by the Bank is in the direction of faster inflation.
It says: 'GDP data suggest that output was closer to potential by the end of
last year than previously thought.'
In spite of the downward revision in the short term, the Bank's view of the
annual inflation rate in two years is virtually unchanged. It will still be
in the top half of the target range of 1 per cent to 4 per cent in 1996 if
base rates are not increased.
Furthermore, the report argues that new inflationary risks have emerged in
the last three months. In its May report the Bank cited three inflationary
concerns, rapid money-supply growth; a rise in nominal earnings; and high
inflation expectations in the financial markets. While those risks have not
worsened, and money-supply growth has in slowed, the report adds three more
dangers.
The first is that 'commodity prices will continue to rise rapidly, pushing
up producers' output prices.' The Bank says that 'because world demand is
still sluggish, big increases in commodity prices are unlikely to continue
for long enough to have a serious impact on domestic inflation'. But it
adds: 'Further supply-side shocks would alter the outlook.'
The second risk is that profit margins, particularly in the retail sector,
may rebound after all. 'It is not clear yet,' says the report, 'whether the
structural changes in retailing which have helped to reduce margins are
permanent.'
The third danger is that the economy may be closer to its full potential
than has been projected. The Bank says this possibility has been raised by
'recent increases in land prices and costs in the construction sector'. It
also cites reports of recruitment difficulties in some sectors.
The Bank admits, however, that the risks are not all on one side. The recent
unexpectedly good retail price figures could result in a reduction of
inflation expectations. And it says says that headline unemployment figures
may be 'exaggerating the speed at which the labour market is tightening and
thus exaggerating the upward pressure on earnings'.
The Bank ends by restating that 'the stance of monetary policy must be set
on the basis of a judgment of where inflation will be in some two years or
so. This is especially important at turning points in official interest
rates.'
The report warns that 'the pressures for higher inflation in the future may
be building up even as the published inflation rate for the past continues
to fall.'
Inflation Report August 1994. Bulletin Group, Economics Division, Bank of
England, Threadneedle Street, London EC2R 8AH or selected bookshops. Pounds
4.
</TEXT>
<XX>
