<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Friendly letters give way to despair: Robert Taylor on the
lack of trust in negotiations over the signal workers' pay claim
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The signalling dispute is turning into one of the most serious industrial
conflicts for a long time. Yesterday's failure by the conciliation service
Acas to find enough common ground between the two sides to bring them back
to the negotiating table indicates that the railway network faces weekly
shutdowns into the autumn.
Only last Wednesday hopes started to rise for the settlement of a dispute
that has started to exasperate both sides. The exchange of friendly letters
between Mr Bob Horton, Railtrack chairman, and Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT's
general secretary, seemed to suggest that the two would soon be back at Acas
making a deal.
It has not turned out that way. Seasoned Acas officials have given up in
despair.
Inevitably Railtrack and the RMT have different versions about what has been
going on during the past few days.
The company is convinced that the union has never been serious about having
negotiations aimed at resolving the dispute. Management believes the union
leadership is growing increasingly out of touch with the mood of the
normally moderate signalling workers and the union is using the grievances
of the men in a wider political game to undermine the privatisation of the
railway network.
The company says that it showed a willingness to move in the talks through
Acas by even agreeing that some of the proposed 6 per cent unconsolidated
pay supplement should be integrated into signallers' basic rates, a move it
had resisted before.
According to Mr David Armstrong, the company's chief negotiator, Railtrack
also offered to have a week of non-stop negotiations on the entire
restructuring package for signalling staff which, if successful, would have
allowed the company to resolve the 'short-term payments problem'.
The union has rejected such peace offers, insisting that the signalling
staff claim for an interim payment must be settled before restructuring
talks start. In the opinion of Railtrack the RMT has not moved an inch since
the conflict started eight weeks ago.
The RMT insists that it has put a number of proposals to Acas in the past
few days that show the union is ready to be flexible. These included an
attempt to persuade the company to set out the efficiency savings that would
come from the specific proposals on changing working practices contained in
its restructuring package.
But Mr Vernon Hince, the RMT's assistant general secretary, said last night
that Railtrack had 'never addressed our claim seriously since June 8'.
The company's exasperation can be seen in its decision to heighten the
public rhetoric. Railtrack plans to decide its next step later this week.
The company said: 'We believe the RMT is out of touch with the views of
their signalling staff.'
That assertion may be tested soon. One option is for Railtrack to hold its
own ballot of the men in dispute to find out what they think.
For the first time yesterday Mr Armstrong said the offer was now a rise of
7.2 per cent on earnings for signalling workers between April 4 and October
1 and a restructuring payment from October 1 which would provide increases
on basic rates of up to 26 per cent, giving overall earnings improvements of
up to 10 per cent.
These figures look more attractive than those of eight weeks ago. The union
insists they have never been on the negotiating table.
Once more the two sides seem unable to agree on basic facts. It is this lack
of trust between the RMT and Railtrack that lies at the heart of the
conflict, with the government shifting day-to-day between being intransigent
and conciliatory.
</TEXT>
