<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Court radio ruling shows loophole
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further consolidation of the commercial-radio industry seems possible after
a High Court judge yesterday approved a scheme designed to circumvent the
existing provisions of the Broadcasting Act 1990.
The broadcasting industry has been awaiting the ruling over the legality of
the Radio Authority's decision to approve a scheme allowing Emap, the media
group, to have a stake in eight large metropolitan licences - two more than
allowed under the act.
The judgment appears to expose a loophole in the 1990 Broadcasting Act which
might require legislation to close.
Under the scheme Emap, which runs the commercial stations Radio City and
Kiss FM, proposes to extend the number of licences it holds from three to
eight by taking over Trans World Communications (TWC).
To get around the upper limit Emap devised a new corporate structure to
enable two of its licences to be 'warehoused'.
The scheme - sanctioned by the Radio Authority - involves a 'deadlocked'
company being set up with Emap and Schoders, its merchant bankers. Each
would own 50 per cent of the share capital of the new company which would
hold the two Radio City licences.
Mr Justice Schiemann yesterday dismissed an application from Guardian Media
Group, which publishes The Guardian newspaper and holds 20 per cent of TWC's
shares, for the Radio Authority's decision to be subject to judicial review.
Guardian argued that the authority had acted beyond its powers in approving
an 'artificial device' designed to evade the restrictions.
The judge ruled, however, that under the proposed structure Schroders would
not be a nominee of Emap nor act under its control.
He also ruled that the Radio Authority had not acted outside its powers.
Parliament could have legislated to prevent such schemes being devised but
it had not done so, he ruled. The authority was therefore entitled to
approve Emap's scheme. The judge refused Guardian Media Group leave to take
its case to the Court of Appeal.
Lawyers for Guardian said it would consider making its own application for
an appeal hearing.
The Radio Authority yesterday made clear that it would reserve its views on
any similar schemes until after any possible appeal and after it had
consulted its members.
The Radio Authority wants to simplify commercial radio ownership rules which
are based on a point system linked to the size of stations.
TWC said last night that it was considering its position and would give its
advice to shareholders in due course.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Trans World Communications.
    Guardian Media Group.
    EMAP.
</CO>
