<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Leyland site to be business park
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Part of the former Leyland Daf site at Leyland, Lancashire, is to be
redeveloped at a cost of Pounds 70m, with the aim of attracting up to 4,000
new jobs during the next 10 years.
Launching the scheme to develop more than 1.3m sq ft of new industrial and
commercial accommodation, Lancashire Enterprises said yesterday that the
centrepiece of the development would be a rail-freight terminal linking the
site with the international European rail network.
The new private terminal will compete with Railtrack's terminals in
Liverpool and Manchester.
Mr Jim Mason, Lancashire Enterprises chairman, said: 'We expect our terminal
to be operating in about 18 months. It will be the only link into the
west-coast line between Crewe and Carlisle and we will exploit this
position.'
Lancashire Enterprises, a development consultancy set up by the county
council in 1982 but now a private company, bought the site last year from
Arthur Andersen, receivers to Leyland Daf. The consultancy leased the
assembly plant to Leyland Trucks, the company sold to a management buy-out
team after the collapse of Leyland Daf.
This company now employs 700 people on the site. A further 800 work for more
than 15 other companies, many in the automotive sector.
Negotiations to acquire 60 acres of adjacent fields will increase the site
to 306 acres.
</TEXT>
