FT  03 AUG 94 / Postal union is warned on protests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Royal Mail is trying to stop its employees from campaigning against the
government's proposed privatisation of the service.
It has warned officials of the Union of Communication Workers that it will
take disciplinary action against staff who wear anti-privatisation badges or
stickers produced by the union on their uniforms or who put them on Royal
Mail vehicles.
Mrs Jane Kitchen, operational developments manager in Sheffield, told the
union that drivers were being instructed 'in as non-threatening a way as
possible' to inform staff that display of stickers and badges could lead to
disciplinary action.
Royal Mail's rules on the wearing of badges point out that 'private badges
may be worn on duty, provided they are not obtrusive and are not badges of a
political party or organisation'.
The tough attitude of managers has led to disciplinary action being taken
against a union member in the Warwick and Leamington area who was
distributing the union's anti-privatisation leaflets in the sorting office.
Her appeal against the disiplinary action is to be held on Friday.
Letters, Page 14
