<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / CBI rejects Portillo's call to cut business aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry yesterday came down firmly against
sweeping cuts in state support for business as the fierce debate over the
government's public spending plans gathered momentum at Westminster.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said the organisation supported the
government's 'existing tight programme totals' including the maintenance of
spending by the Department of Trade and Industry.
In yesterday's statement Mr Davies focused particularly on support for
British exports, saying it would be 'a great mistake' to cut government
backing for overseas trade.
He said there was 'solid research' showing that the benefit derived from
government support for exports - particularly those of smaller companies in
new markets - far outweighed the cost. Many DTI programmes were 'in effect
an investment in individual success'.
But he said public spending should not be allowed to 'overrun', while the
government's Pounds 5bn contingency reserve should be 'used to reduce
borrowing, not allocated to programmes'.
Mr Davies's intervention followed a call by Mr Michael Portillo, the new
employment secretary, for the DTI to accept drastic cuts in a large number
of its programmes.
The call, which came in a leaked letter to Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade
and industry secretary, was widely interpreted as an early sign of tensions
in the cabinet that could arise as the government struggles to stick to its
tough spending targets in this year's Budget.
It threatened to shake the uneasy truce between the left and right wings of
the Conservative party less than two weeks after Mr John Major's cabinet
reshuffle.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, yesterday responded to
the signs of increased ministerial tension by trying to drive a wedge
between Mr Portillo and Mr Jonathan Aitken, his successor as chief Treasury
secretary.
Mr Cook wrote to Mr Aitken pointing out that his Thanet constituency had
recently benefited from regional assistance and asking whether he shared Mr
Portillo's view that it should be scrapped.
'I am sure your constituents would also be interested to know whether you
share his conclusion that there is no strong case for retaining development
areas and that they should move out of the area to find work,' Mr Cook said.
Rightwing Tory MPs have voiced confidence that Mr Aitken will take as hard a
line on spending as his predecessor.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
