<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / DGB backs part-time working
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German government is not doing enough to encourage part-time work, Ms
Ursula Engelen-Kefer, deputy head of the trade union federation (DGB), said
yesterday. Ms Engelen-Kefer said the current arrangements for part-time work
are not flexible enough, particularly for women with families. Last June
Chancellor Helmut Kohl supported a plan to privatise more of the state
sector, cut unemployment benefits after a certain period of time, and
introduce more part-time work as a means of cutting unemployment. But Ms
Engelen-Kefer said the legal basis for part-time work, including insurance,
health and pension schemes, was inadequate. Recent studies have shown that
more than 2.5m Germans would prefer to work part-time. About 15.5 per cent
of the labour force already works part-time, most of whom are women in
low-paid jobs.
