<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 94 / Heseltine 'excluded' Treasury from DTI reviews
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine ordered the exclusion of Treasury officials from
fundamental spending reviews at the Department of Trade and Industry. He
then prematurely wound up the exercise four months before it was due to be
completed.
The trade and industry secretary is understood to have said that the working
parties, which involved members of the DTI and Treasury officials, were
taking up 'too much time' and that he had his own ways of scrutinising
budgets.
Mr Heseltine's action in February throws further light on the friction
between him and Mr Michael Portillo, the new employment secretary, over the
public spending review.
Their differences came into the open earlier this week with the leaking of a
letter in which Mr Portillo, then chief secretary to the Treasury, upbraided
Mr Heseltine for failing to support policies to cut taxation and spending.
Mr Portillo pressed Mr Heseltine to accept drastic cuts in a large number of
DTI programmes and to end support for shipbuilding and an independent UK
space programme.
Civil servants said yesterday the tone of Mr Portillo's letter may have been
influenced by Mr Heseltine's premature winding up of the reviews and the
fact that he barred Treasury officials from the final meetings.
Government officials, however, also said they were not surprised by the
letter. 'The debate that has surfaced about what is the role of the DTI is
one that has gone on for a long time, and it has never been resolved,' said
one official. 'This time it has emerged in a sharpish form.'
The reviews were devised to examine what Whitehall departments should be
doing. The DTI review began late last year, with a number of working
parties.
Two months into the planned six-month review, Mr Heseltine said he wanted
the working groups to be wound up within 2 1/2 weeks and that Treasury
officials should be barred from attending their final deliberations. The
groups concluded their work without the Treasury being part of the process.
The Treasury said yesterday that it could not comment on actions by
officials in another department. The DTI also said it was unable to comment.
</TEXT>
