<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Wellcome wanted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and SAQIB QURESHI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wellcome, the UK pharmaceuticals group, forged ahead 14 3/4 to 648p after
one of its competitors was obliged to withdraw a key treatment for epilepsy
in the US.
Carter-Wallace, of the US, sent a letter to 240,000 doctors advising
immediate withdrawal of patients from its Felbatol treatment after the
appearance of side effects. It was one of three new entrants into an
estimated Dollars 550m market dominated, according to analysts, by cheap
generic products, many of which produce side effects.
Wellcome's Lamictal is one of two other new products expected to gain
approval shortly from the US Food and Drug Administration.
Although there has been some concern that the FDA is clamping down on new
products following restraint on recent applications by SmithKline Beecham
and Merck, one analyst said he had spoken to the FDA and was confident that
the approval process would not be slowed down.
The latest figures from Abbey National, the second of the big banking groups
to report interim results, saw the share price fall 12 to 385p. The profits
of Pounds 423m were above expectations but, as with Lloyds Bank, they were
increased by a sharp fall in the provisions for bad debts and there was
disappointment that Abbey's share of the mortgage market was less than
expected.
The bank also announced an insurance joint venture with Commercial Union,
which rose 2 on the news but slipped back to close a net 2 softer at 548p.
The deal is expected to squeeze rival Sun Alliance, which receded 9 to 322p
as two large blocks of shares were placed in the market.
National Westminster Bank, which reports today, improved 5 to 453p, with a
block of 1m shares going through the Seaq system at 451p.
Tobacco and insurance conglomerate BAT Industries was the most heavily
traded stock in London as a result of technical trading in the shares and in
put options.
A block of 9.5m was traded at 444 1/2 p and 9,500 short-dated puts
representing 9.5m shares were also sold. Initially, it appeared that the
trade might be a way of getting into the shares at 434p, close to the price
of the shares after the payment of the 8.5p dividend next week. The stock
ended the day 5 1/2 higher at 447p on turnover of 30m, the highest for more
than a year.
Mining group RTZ jumped 21 1/2 to 884p on news of increased copper
production. There was also talk of a buy recommendation from BZW, but the
house was unavailable for comment late yesterday.
Oil shares rose in early trade as the price of Brent crude was pushed higher
on supply worries as a result of the strikes in Nigeria. Brent crude
deliverable in September broke above Dollars 19 a barrel, its highest level
in 15 months. Shell Transport added 7 at 737p, British Petroleum firmed a
half-penny but ended a penny down on the day at 411 1/2 p as US investors
sold into strength ahead of second-quarter figures today.
Retailer WH Smith was the focus for bearish stories which combined to push
the shares down 7 to 452p. Prominent among these was the suggestion that the
newspaper price war may prompt News International and The Telegraph group to
consider setting up their own wholesale distribution systems. There was also
talk that the newspaper industry was considering putting pressure on Smith
to reduce its charges. Finally, VAT fears were also circulating, further
undermining the Smith share price. The move by the Independent newspaper to
cut its cover price to 30p, the same level as the Telegraph, ruffled
feathers among publishing stocks. Telegraph shares slipped 3 to 365p.
Suggestions that motor dealer T. Cowie may announce a lucrative deal
together with today's interim figures helped the shares harden 4 1/2 to
268p. Hopes of an important order also kept GKN 2 ahead at 622p.
A broker's recommendation powered engineering group Glynwed International,
the shares firming 3 to 377p. NatWest Securities said: 'As the recovery in
the UK continues to gather pace and profits growth outstrips that of the
market in general we believe there is plenty of scope for further
outperformance.'
Conglomerate Harrisons &amp; Crosfield gained 7 at 179p as the market
appreciated the group's Pounds 167m sale of its Indonesian plantations,
announced late on Friday.
Analysts at BZW, which remains neutral on the stock, welcomed the deal,
saying Harrisons had received a better price than anticipated. In addition,
they said the deal was not as dilutive of share earnings as originally
feared and had favourable tax implications for the company.
A buy recommendation from Goldman Sachs helped Trafalgar House firm 2 1/2 to
80p. There was good demand for Channel tunnel operator Eurotunnel, which has
received approval for a provisional licence to operate a limited passenger
service. The shares rose 15 to 329p.
Construction group Ashtead jumped 21 to 383p after announcing a 150 per cent
full-year profits increase to Pounds 7.1m. RMC gained 6 at 958p as Kleinwort
Benson upgraded its profits forecast for 1996. Chemicals group Wolstenholme
Rink climbed 20 to 723p, reflecting demand in a weak market.
</TEXT>
