<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A large deal in the traded options sector was the only outstanding feature
in an otherwise dull day in the derivatives, writes Joel Kibazo.
In traded options, the day's big trade was carried out in BAT Industries
stock options. Kleinwort Benson was said to have sold 9,500 of the August
550 puts to Smith New Court at 116p. Dealers suggested that the deal had
been timed to coincide with next week's dividend payout in BAT.
That trade helped to raise total volume in the sector to 27,320 contracts by
the close. Some 5,378 were dealt in the FT-SE 100 option and 3,595 in the
Euro FT-SE option. Among the other stock options, RTZ saw business of 1,279
lots and 1,078 were traded in Asda.
In futures, dealers also reported a cautious session, with few of the big
institutions willing to deal.
Having opened at 3,090, the September futures contract on the FT-SE 100
moved forward on sporadic buying by independent(local) traders and some
buying from UBS. It reached the day's high of 3,119 at mid-morning, before
profit-taking left it trading around the 3,100 over the next few hours.
A firm opening on Wall Street brought a renewed advance for the contract and
it finished at 3,108, up 13 from its previous close and at a good premium to
cash of 11 points. Volume, at 7,398 lots, was poor.
</TEXT>
