<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / International Company News: US and Japan groups in Dollars
500m chip move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Texas Instruments of the US and Hitachi of Japan have agreed to form a joint
venture to build a Dollars 500m semiconductor chip plant in Texas. It will
be the first joint venture semiconductor manufacturing facility in the US.
The companies announced plans to begin construction of the plant next year,
with production to begin in 1996. The plant will produce 16 and 64 megabit
dynamic random-access memory chips (D-Rams) - the next two generations of
data storage chips for use in a broad variety of computer and consumer
electronics products.
TI and Hitachi will hold a majority equity stake in the joint venture and
plan to seek equity investments from other parties. All products produced at
the plant will go directly to TI and Hitachi for sale to their customers.
The joint venture is subject to regulatory approval in the US.
The joint venture follows six years of research and development
collaboration between TI and Hitachi on successive generations of memory
chips.
Rising costs have led to several collaborative efforts in the memory chip
business including another TI joint venture with Acer of Taiwan.
</TEXT>
