<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Exceptional costs hit Andrews Sykes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLARE GASCOIGNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Restructuring will continue to depress Andrews Sykes, the specialist
industrial services group which yesterday announced a fall into the red for
the year to end-March.
Exceptional items of Pounds 4.12m, half of which related to the disposal of
non-core businesses, resulted in a pre-tax loss of Pounds 4.74m, against
profits of Pounds 1.27m.
Mr Eric Hook, appointed chief executive on May 12 following a boardroom
coup, said further rationalisation and reorganisation costs 'will adversely
affect the results for the year to March 1995'.
Turnover fell 6 per cent, from Pounds 56.2m to Pounds 52.9m. Operating
profits dropped from Pounds 4.2m to Pounds 1.2m; only Pounds 200,000 of this
was generated in the UK, compared with Pounds 3.4m the previous year.
Exceptional losses on the disposal of two subsidiaries - Centahire, the
small tool hire business based in the north-east, and Kocoverk, the 51 per
cent owned Swedish group - amounted to Pounds 2.05m. Other exceptional items
included redundancy costs of Pounds 670,000 (Pounds 844,000); a property
write-down of Pounds 891,000; a stock and other asset write-off of Pounds
367,000 and other exceptional costs of Pounds 140,000.
Mr Hook said further asset disposals and a cost reduction programme would be
necessary to reduce year-end gearing of 256 per cent. Since then the company
has closed a centralised pump repair facility in Tipton, West Midlands, and
withdrawn from Hungary.
'There is now a need to refocus management attention on the group's core
activities of pumping, heating and air-conditioning and, in particular, the
UK-based hire business,' he said.
Losses per share were 40.6p (0.5p), and no final dividend is proposed (3p,
totalling 4.4p for the year). Although the group was able in May to pay
arrears of dividend on the convertible preference shares of 7p per share,
payment due in June was again deferred.
</TEXT>
