<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / TV satellite operator faces revolt by users
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Societe Europeenne des Satellites, the Luxembourg company that operates the
Astra television satellite system, is facing a potential user revolt over
managerial instability at the group. At stake could be as much as Pounds 1bn
of business, as Europe's main satellite broadcasters plan to introduce
digital satellite television channels over the next few years.
Some users of Astra satellites were alarmed at what they saw as an attempted
coup against Mr Pierre Meyrat, director-general of SES. Mr Meyrat is
credited with creating one of the world's most successful satellite
television companies. An attempt was made to remove him last month by a
group of directors and shareholders including the two SES vice-chairmen, Mr
Romain Bausch, chairman of the SNCI bank of Luxembourg, and Count Roland
Kergorlay, a private investor. Mr Meyrat ultimately received widespread
support at a board meeting last week.
One Astra user said yesterday he would be wary about signing up for the vast
investment needed to introduce digital channels if the SES director-general
could be removed without warning.
A number of users wrote to SES in support of Mr Meyrat, including British
Sky Broadcasting and Deutsche Bundespost Telekom, which has a 16.6 per cent
stake in SES. Some are seeking assurances of managerial stability and are
demanding to be kept better informed about the company.
Unless assurances are received, at least one big Astra customer is prepared
to go to Astra's rival Eutelsat, which is owned by Europe's
telecommunications organisations, for its new digital business.
SES operates three 16-channel television satellites and plans to launch a
fourth in the autumn. The fifth and six satellites are scheduled to be
dedicated to digital television and should be capable of broadcasting more
than 150 channels across Europe.
