<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Cattle prices hit by EU export curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cattle prices at UK livestock auctions have fallen by up to 30 per cent
following last week's introduction of European Union curbs on British beef
exports which are aimed at stopping the spread of 'mad cow' disease.
Some butchers were also reporting a fall in beef sales, the Meat and
Livestock Commission said yesterday. But it was unsure if this was a
response to the latest publicity over bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE)
or the hot weather encouraging people to eat salads.
Livestock prices have fallen even though many farmers are holding their
animals back from market in the face of the new rules, which state that
carcass beef for export must come from herds free of BSE for six years,
rather than two years previously.
The price falls mainly affect beef which is processed into meat pies and
sausages and industry sources said it would be some time before there was
any impact on retail prices.
The Livestock Auctioneers' Association said yesterday it was seeking an
urgent meeting with Mr William Waldegrave, the new agriculture minister,
over the restrictions agreed by EU farm ministers two weeks ago.
Mr Jim Watson, association president, said prices of cull cows, or old dairy
cows, had fallen by 30 per cent, while those of young steers and heifers
were down by about 10 per cent. 'It's because there's too much beef on the
market,' he said. 'At a stroke, we've lost our export market overnight.'
Carcass, or bone-in, beef accounts for 84 per cent of British beef exports
to the EU. Of the 107,000 tonnes of bone-in beef exported last year, cull
cows made up 70 per cent, with young cattle accounting for the rest.
Because the cows are old, it is more difficult to trace their history and
more likely they will have spent some time on a farm with BSE. Some 52 per
cent of dairy herds have had at least one case of the disease.
Mr Watson said the agriculture ministry was creating too much paperwork for
farmers and delaying export of the minority of animals that could be given a
clean bill of health.
Mr Martin Burtt, chairman of the National Farmers' Union livestock
committee, said a two-tier market had opened up, with animals that carry
BSE-free certification commanding a 70 per cent premium in some markets.
He urged the ministry to circumvent the Data Protection Act and give farmers
names and addresses of BSE-free farms so they could trace the history of the
animals they want to sell.
He said the ministry received 7,000 inquiries from farmers last Friday. The
agriculture ministry said its computer experts were looking at ways to help
farmers trace animals' health history.
</TEXT>
