<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One American influence on Cuba that seems to have developed deep roots is
baseball. It is the national sport - and then some. A whole different ball
game (BBC 2 at 7.40), the programme that travels the world to reveal how
important sport is to some cultures, looks at the phenomenon. Castro is a
great fan; seven players have made it into politics; yet for the stars the
real money lies across the Florida Straits, a constant temptation which few
apparently dare succumb to.
Keith Floyd seems much happier eating his way through Italy than wrestling
with the mysteries of south east Asian cuisine. This week (BBC 2 at 8.30) he
has reached Umbria, and after a spot of grilled perch for breakfast he goes
mushroom hunting before settling down to the cooking - beef and mushrooms in
red wine.
Yet another programme which has successfully made the jump from radio to
television is Just a Minute (ITV at 10.40.)
Robert Jahn was Dean of Engineering at Princeton University until his
interest in ESP lost him the respect of his colleagues. He is the latest
Heretic on BBC 2 at 10pm.
</TEXT>
