<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Court to rule on stalling of Maxwell probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the largest accountancy firm, has been granted leave to
go to the courts in an effort to stall a wide-ranging professional
investigation into its audit of the Maxwell business empire.
If the ruling goes in the firm's favour it would be seen as a serious blow
to self-regulation of professional bodies.
The action follows the launch in May last year by the Joint Disciplinary
Scheme, the profession's most senior regulatory body, of an investigation
into pensions and related transactions within the Maxwell companies.
The attempt has been triggered by a precedent-setting judgment in April
which allowed Price Waterhouse to stall an investigation by the regulator of
PW's audit of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
The ruling - which was argued on the grounds that the BCCI case was highly
unusual and complex - meant that no inquiry could take place until civil and
criminal actions relating to the bank and its auditors were complete. This
is unlikely until the next century.
The Joint Disciplinary Scheme, which is operated by the UK's chartered and
certified accountancy bodies, only investigates matters of the most serious
public interest.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand said yesterday that it had formally requested suspension
of the inquiry in February 'on the basis that any such inquiry could be
prejudicial to justice'.
After the regulator refused this demand in March, Coopers formally requested
a review last month. It confirmed yesterday that it had been granted leave
to seek judicial review by Mr Justice Latham. No date has been set for a
hearing although it is expected to take place relatively soon.
A number of professional firms - both in accountancy and in other sectors -
have been reviewing the Price Waterhouse judgment in detail and considering
attempts to use similar stalling tactics.
Regulators had been expecting other firms to test the judgment more broadly,
and some are believed to welcome the chance to test its limits.
The regulator's case has not been helped because it has in the past delayed
the launch of several investigations. In the case of Polly Peck
International, it waited until this May, more than three years after the
collapse of the company, before launching its investigation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Coopers and Lybrand.
    Maxwell Communications Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
