<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Insurance watchdog says why he quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Julian Farrand, who resigned as insurance ombudsman last Thursday and is
to be pensions ombudsman, yesterday called for his new office to be given
responsibility for complaints about personal pensions sold to people
transferring out of occupational schemes.
He also criticised the Personal Investment Authority, the controversial new
watchdog to protect the private investor. He said it had significantly
reduced the role of the insurance ombudsman by creating a new office of PIA
ombudsman.
Mr Farrand said yesterday that he had resigned as insurance ombudsman after
a long period of 'disillusionment' over the role's future.
He added: 'I preferred the challenge of being in a developed and enlarged
role to remaining in something with a diminishing significance.'
He said he had been searching for new appointments for some months as his
role had been increasingly squeezed by the expansion of the authority.
His resignation followed the news last Wednesday that his application to
become pensions ombudsman had been accepted. He takes over on September 1.
Mr Farrand had already hinted in evidence earlier this year to the Commons
Treasury committee that he was unhappy with the new structures being
implemented for the regulation of invest-ment.
One particularly contentious issue has been the fact that there is a ceiling
of Pounds 50,000 on the award the PIA ombudsman can make a
financial-services organisation pay. This compares with a maximum of Pounds
100,000 under the insurance-ombudsman scheme.
Mr Farrand said it remained unclear which body would take on the role of
dealing with complaints about pension transfers and opt-outs if the rulings
of the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, were not
accepted.
He said shifting this responsibility to the pensions ombudsman had 'some
sort of logic and clarity, and would be a little less confusing for the
consumer'.
While SIB has yet to publish its plans for dealing with compensation to
customers who have suffered as a result of poor advice to take a pension
transfer, there is little sign that it believes the pensions ombudsman is
best placed to take on this role.
SIB believes that most complaints will centre on the marketing side of
pensions rather than on their administration, and so would fall more to the
PIA ombudsman.
</TEXT>
