<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Prudential urges law shake-up in pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prudential Corporation has launched a campaign to lobby the government for
pension law to be simplified.
It is urging standardisation, perhaps on a statutory basis, of how to
calculate the value of a lump sum which might be transferred from a former
employer's pension scheme to a personal plan.
It argues also that personal pensions should be simplified to make them more
genuinely portable.
At the moment, for example, people with personal pensions who then move to
jobs where they can join a company scheme are unable to maintain their
personal pensions. They are, however, allowed to top up the occupational
scheme with free-standing additional voluntary contributions.
Although Prudential has considerable influence as the largest pension
provider, its image was tarnished recently by the leak of a paper from the
life industry's regulator indicating that it was the subject of an informal
investigation.
Its stance on pension transfers has also been criticised. While there are
cases it does not take because they do not make financial sense for the
customer, in other circumstances it behaves unlike other life insurers in
saying that it can give the customer only information and not advice on
whether to take a pension transfer, because the benefits of doing so are not
guaranteed.
On transfer values, Prudential said the difficulties arose from the scope in
existing arrangements for wide variations in the calculations. These
differences could prove decisive in the consideration of a pension transfer.
At present, actuaries have broad guidelines on how to take account of
inflation prospects, discretionary increases in benefits and expected
investment returns.
Prudential is organising a delegation of industry representatives and MPs to
discuss these issues with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, in the autumn.
</TEXT>
