<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Gloom on chemicals work prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chemicals industry in Cleveland has lost 5,300 jobs since 1981 and is
expected to shed up to 2,000 more by the year 2006, says a report to be
considered by county councillors tomorrow, Chris Tighe writes.
This would cut employment in the county's chemicals sector to 11,200.
Between 1981 and 1993, the chemicals industry's share of total employment in
Cleveland dropped from 9 per cent to 7 per cent.
Asset swaps, plant closures, demergers, selective acquisitions and more
flexible working arrangements have all had an impact on Cleveland as
chemical companies battle to keep a share of an increasingly competitive
industry, often by focusing on core activities, says the report.
The report, by the council's department of environment, development and
transportation, says the county does have some 'core' industries which are
performing well, but much of its employment is in the fluctuating bulk
chemicals sector. It also points to lack of local control as a weakness in
terms of job security.
</TEXT>
