<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Swan takeover talks make slow progress
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Iskandar Safa, the sole prospective bidder for Swan Hunter as a going
concern, yesterday arrived for talks aimed at saving the Tyneside
shipbuilder from closure. Although the talks in London were described as
constructive they ended inconclusively after more than four hours, Chris
Tighe writes.
The meeting between Price Waterhouse, the receiver, and Mr Safa, principal
shareholder of Soffia, the parent company of patrol boat builder
Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie, was organised by shipyard unions.
This was after Price Waterhouse said CMN's offer - in which Pounds 3.5m is
guaranteed - was well below Swans' Pounds 7.5m break-up value.
The two sides indicated it would be two to three weeks before it would be
clear whether agreement could be reached. This would make it impossible to
achieve the deadline of noon tomorrow, set by the Ministry of Defence, for
placing the Pounds 6m, three-month refit of the Royal Fleet Auxiliary tanker
Olwen with Swan Hunter.
An industrial tribunal in Newcastle upon Tyne today begins a test case
hearing at which unions representing former Swans employees will contest the
Department of Employment's handling of payments made following an award by a
tribunal last year. The award was to compensate 430 workers, made redundant
just after the receivers' arrival in May last year, for the lack of a 90-day
consultative period. However many of the workers received little or no
payout.
The unions are challenging the employment department's decision to base its
calculations on eight weeks rather than 12, and to deduct money paid in lieu
of notice and wage arrears payments.
