Surrey, and to Yeovil in Somerset for the first time during the strikes.
This morning the union's leadership will announce plans for next week with a
possible move to a 48-hour period of dis-ruption.
On Thursday the result of the union's ballot of its supervisors will be
announced, and if this produces a majority in support for industrial action
in sympathy with the signalling staff they could join any planned strikes
after August 11.
Railway signal workers in south-west England were yesterday discussing
whether to accept an informal local offer of lump sums, said to be up to
Pounds 800 each, in return for working during strikes ordered by the RMT.
Railtrack said the reported 'offer' to signal workers in some areas was
nothing more than a repackaging of money 'which has always been on the
table'.
