<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / MMC to put more work out to tender
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is to develop further the selective
contracting out of its work on references and demonstrate more fully how it
spends public money.
The changes follow a review commissioned by the government from Price
Waterhouse, the management consultants, on the MMC's financial management.
Price Waterhouse made a number of recommendations on how the management of
the commission's work could be improved. Overall, however, these will not
change greatly the way the commission works.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said the review had concluded
that the commission had been effective in its role as an investigative body
and had carried out its responsibilities 'in an independent, professional
and fair manner'.
One of the most important improvements will be the publication of annual
accounts from 1995-96 in addition to the regular annual review.
The commission will also be increasing the contracting-out of reference
work. It said yesterday it had always used outside contractors, but was
bringing its practices fully into line with European Union rules on open
bidding for public contracts.
Mr Hamilton said the commission would also improve liaison with the Office
of Fair Trading to minimise duplicate burdens on businesses.
The commission employs about 90 staff and has an annual budget of Pounds
5.5m.
</TEXT>
