<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / World Trade News: Juggernauts collide, parts-maker dented
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A privately owned US truck parts maker which has never exported to Japan has
found itself side-swiped in the duel between the trade juggernauts of Tokyo
and Washington, Gordon Cramb writes from Tokyo.
Johnson Industries, based in Urbana, Ohio, was accused by Japanese media
yesterday of pulling out at the last minute after 18 months of negotiations
aimed at supplying Hino Motors, Japan's leading truck maker, with a
component to make its vehicles lighter and thus more fuel-efficient.
The reason for its withdrawal being put about in Tokyo was that the US
economy was now so buoyant that Johnson felt able to reject Hino's order.
The shipment would have been for some 10,000 units worth a total of perhaps
Dollars 1m.
Growth in the US has been running at a rather faster lick than in Japan. The
implication of the disclosure was that US companies need no longer bother
cutting deals with unfamiliar Japanese customers, because they have more
than enough demand at home. Japan's record bilateral trade surplus would
therefore remain undented by the pick-up in the US economy.
Johnson, although it supplies three of the six biggest US truck makers, is a
family-held company which had sales last year estimated at Dollars 25m and
employs 250 people - more than one in every hundred in Urbana. Hino, an
affiliate of Toyota, Japan's biggest car maker, has annual revenues of
Y535.5bn (Dollars 5.4bn) and more than 9,000 staff.
In Tokyo a Hino official confirmed yesterday that Johnson had withdrawn in
May from negotiations to supply aluminium air reservoir tanks for braking
systems, and that his company had turned to domestic suppliers instead.
But he added that Hino had no hand in revealing the breakdown two months
late. Mr Greg Moore, Johnson vice president, said the potential supplier had
been working on an air tank design but that 'the product we were offering
was not matching the specifications they were asking for, and there was a
mismatch. Time ran out for us as a supplying manufacturer.'
He added that his company 'couldn't reach a final contract' for a delivery
which was due in November. 'The way we left it, we needed a new design,' he
added, saying Johnson believed talks on possible future collaboration could
continue.
The saga of the failed talks between Hino and an unnamed Ohio supplier was
aired on Sunday night by Japan's NHK public television network, and other
news media in Tokyo yesterday fingered Johnson as the component maker which
stood Hino up 'because of surging demand by US automakers' in a decision
which came 'despite long-standing US pressure on Japan to buy more autos and
auto parts' from American companies.
Hino would suffer as a result, the reports suggested, because it would not
be able to switch so soon away from the heavier steel reservoir tanks it had
previously used. The Japanese company insisted yesterday, however, that it
would not be adversely affected and had not sought to publicise the
incident.
Nor certainly had Johnson, which said merely that like many possible deals
explored between companies across the world operating in the same sector,
'it had never reached the final specifications'.
Editorial Comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
