<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / World Trade News: Canada and US draw up wheat peace plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US and Canada yesterday announced a preliminary agreement to avert a
damaging trade war over Canadian wheat exports, with Canada agreeing to curb
its wheat sales into the US market for a year.
The pact still must be approved by the Canadian and US cabinets, which are
to take it up today. Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, said the
details would not be announced until final agreement was reached.
'The agreement addresses the immediate problem of a surge in imports of
Canadian grain, while also establishing a process and a reasonable time
frame for addressing on a longer-term basis problems in the grains sector,'
he said.
The pact comes two weeks after a finding by the International Trade
Commission that Canada's 5m tonnes of US wheat sales had done some damage to
the US farm programme. The six commissioners differed widely on the extent
of the damage, with three saying the harm had been minimal and probably
transitory.
Under US law, President Bill Clinton can impose tariffs or quotas on
products found to damage the price support programme. He also has the option
of doing nothing.
But politics has been driving the issue, in the form of three key Democratic
senators from wheat-growing states on the powerful finance committee
insisting Canada unfairly subsidises its wheat.
US farmers themselves receive billions of dollars in grain subsidies.
One of the senators - Mr Max Baucus, chairman of the international trade
subcommittee - said the pact would sharply limit exports from current levels
both on durum wheat and other wheat and would 'go a long way toward
stabilising prices'.
The preliminary agreement has three parts. First, the US one-year import
curb officially began yesterday. Mr Kantor said it would result in 'a
substantial reduction in wheat imports'. That would have happened in any
case, since the 5m tonnes imported in 1993-94 was spurred by unusual
weather-related problems in both the US and Canada which are absent this
year.
The two sides also have agreed to a 12-month 'peace clause' on grains trade
to ensure against 'additional restrictions or countermeasures', with both
countries committed not to take action inconsistent with the North American
Free Trade Area pact or the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
They also agreed to create a joint commission on grains, composed of 6-10
private sector representatives, to study each country's marketing and farm
support systems over the next year. It will seek a longer-term solution to
the grains trade dispute. Its recommendations will not be binding.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
