<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / Berlusconi prepared to change Fininvest plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian prime minister, is willing to consider
changes in the proposals he has made on avoiding a conflict of interest with
his Fininvest business empire.
Hints of flexibility came as he prepared for today's important debate in
parliament on recent incidents when his business interests have clashed with
those of his role as prime minister.
The debate is not a formal vote of confidence, but Mr Berlusconi is expected
to use the occasion to try to recoup some of his battered prestige before
the parliamentary summer break at the end of the week. It will also be an
important test of the unity of the right-wing coalition government.
Mr Berlusconi's proposals for avoiding a conflict of interest were unveiled
on Friday and were based on advice from three lawyers who had originally
been asked to report by the end of September.
However, President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro has already ensured that part of the
plan will have to be rewritten. He said that the president could not be
asked to help nominate a five-person commission to monitor any conflict of
interest, as suggested by Mr Berlusconi. That was outside the president's
constitutional authority, he said.
Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of the populist Northern League, a coalition
partner, has promised to introduce new proposals during the debate. The
League leader, who has been a constant thorn in Mr Berlusconi's side, says
he is determined to prevent the prime minister having any influence over the
management of Fininvest, Italy's second largest private company.
Mr Berlusconi has let it be known that his own proposals can be
reconsidered. But he is adamant about retaining ownership of Fininvest,
albeit at a distance. Mr Bossi said over the weekend that ownership should
be placed in a foundation, but did not elaborate.
The former communist Party of the Democratic Left has said in the past that
the problems can only be solved by Mr Berlusconi selling Fininvest. But most
now recognise this is easier said than done.
Any proposal will have to pass through parliament as a law, with discussion
beginning in September. The League has the power to undermine the
legislation, and Mr Bossi's partners in the right-wing coalition were
nervous yesterday that he might threaten sabotage or an alliance with the
opposition. However, Mr Bossi was thought likely to want to keep Mr
Berlusconi guessing.
Also influencing today's debate will be the nomination of a new chairman for
Italy's anti-trust authority, following the death at the weekend of Mr
Francesco Saja, a former head of the constitutional court. Mr Saja had
played a significant role in trying to introduce the concept of anti-trust
rules to cartel-ridden Italy.
The nomination is controlled by the speakers of both houses of parliament,
who have also been proposed to nominate Mr Berlusconi's conflict of interest
commission.
</TEXT>
