<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 94 / China flies in the face of satellite parking convention
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
China has become the first country to flout the conventions of space by
parking a satellite in a position that could interfere with other satellites
and hinder the Asian ambitions of international broadcasting companies.
There are no laws governing the launch and positioning of satellites above
the earth. But it has become a convention that agreement with the owners of
adjacent satellites is reached through the International Telecommunication
Union (ITU), a Geneva-based United Nations agency that registers satellites.
Industry executives said the Chinese launch of a commercial satellite 12
days ago was the first time that a country has launched a satellite without
the agreement of other operators of satellites near the intended position of
the new satellite.
They believe that if the satellite is used as planned in coming weeks it
will interfere with signals from a planned Japanese telecommunications
satellite and a satellite operated by Rimsat, a US company, to beam
television to India. They also say that some of the Chinese satellite's 24
transponders, or transmitters, may be inoperable because of interference
caused by its proximity to the other satellites.
In this case, the business strategies of some of the US's top broadcasters
could be badly affected. Turner Broadcasting, Home Box Office, and Viacom,
which owns MTV, have all signed up to use the satellite to further their
ambitions in Asian broadcasting.
In addition, the China Telecommunications Broadcasting Satellite Corporation
has signed a lease agreement for eight of the satellite's transponders for
both television and telecommunications.
The Japanese government is believed to be angry about the Chinese
government's behaviour. It had talks in Beijing last week which ended in
failure.
The state-of-the-art Chinese satellite, is owned by APT Satellite, a Hong
Kong-registered company controlled by three Chinese government ministries
together with investors from Singapore, Thailand and Macao. The company's
seventh shareholder is a company owned by the Kuomintang, Taiwan's ruling
Nationalist party.
The satellite, known as Apstar 1, was launched from Xichang, Sichuan, on
July 21. It is estimated to have cost APT about Dollars 130m to buy, launch
and insure. Its twin, Apstar 2, is due for launch early next year.
Of crucial importance to existing operators is the positioning of a new
satellite. In general, the industry requires 2-2.5 degrees of separation -
1,488km - between satellites so that respective 'footprints' do not cause
interference.
The Chinese government last year registered Apstar 1's position, above the
equator in geostationary orbit, at 131 degrees east with the ITU. However,
at 132 degrees east is a planned Japanese communications satellite and at
130 degrees east is Rimsat1, which broadcasts for the Sun TV group of India.
Mr Yang Xueming, director of marketing at APT, denies that Apstar 1 will
cause other operators any difficulties.
However, satellite industry executives in Hong Kong said they were concerned
that Apstar 1 was launched without completing the industry's three-stage
co-ordination process.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CNZ  China, Asia.
    HKZ  Hong Kong, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
