<HEADLINE>
FT  01 AUG 94 / The Markets: Testing time for coffee and metals -
Commodities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading commodity markets enter this week with some serious question marks
hanging over them.
After the recent fireworks, coffee prices have been settling back and
traders will be looking for signs of consolidation to stave off a feared
major sell-off by the US investment funds whose buying was so influential in
the gains of the past month or so.
At the London Metal Exchange meanwhile, the copper and aluminium markets
will be watched with interest, not to say anxiety, following recent retreats
from long-time highs.
Now that the Brazilian industry and commerce ministry has issued its
assessment of the damage done to the country's coffee crop by the frosts of
June 27 and July 11, and with fears of further frosts in growing areas
receding, the coffee market has to prove that it can thrive in the rarefied
atmosphere above Dollars 3,000 a tonne.
So far the retreat from last month's Dollars 4,000-plus highs has not
threated to carry the London Commodity Exchange September futures position
below the Dollars 3,076 a tonne ruling immediately before the second frost -
last week's low was Dollars 3,362. But with the Brazilian coffee frost
season now entering its final month, speculators, while remaining reluctant
to go 'short' in this market, could be looking for opportunities to take
profits.
The LME copper and aluminium markets are in a comparable position.
Copper last week continued its retreat from the previous week's two-year
highs, while aluminium, having broken through support at Dollars 1,500 a
tonne for three months delivery, dipped below Dollars 1,450 at one point.
Both markets steadied towards the end of the week, however, and they remain
within reach of the highs.
Analysts are for the most part cautiously bullish about the price prospects
for these metals once the current consolidation phase is completed. But, as
in the coffee market, the potential weight of investment fund selling is
seen as a serious threat in the short term.
</TEXT>
